      "content": "i get that they're both frameworks, but it feels like one of them is more \"correct\" in a modern context. like, isnt the idea of national sovereignty just a way to ignore basic human suffering? it feels like the humanitarian side is the only one that actually aligns with universal ethics. can you explain why someone would argue that border security is even a valid moral position if it leads to people getting hurt?",
